<p>Compute P(F &gt; 3.894), with <em>df</em><sub>1</sub> =3D 3 and <em>df</=
em><sub>2</sub> =3D 18</p>

<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Introductory_Statistics/Mostly_Harmle=
ss_Statistics_(Webb)/09:_Hypothesis_Tests_and_Confidence_Intervals_for_Two_=
Populations/9.04:_Two_Variance_or_Standard_Deviation_F-Test" class=3D"mt-se=
ction"><span id=3D"Solution_3"></span><h6 class=3D"editable">Solution</h6>

<p>In Excel, use the function F.DIST(x,deg_freedom1,deg_freedom2,cumulative=
). Always use TRUE for the cumulative. The F.DIST function will find the pr=
obability (area) below F. Since we want the area above F we would need to a=
lso use the complement rule. The formula would be =3D1-F.DIST(3.894,3,18,TR=
UE) =3D 0.0263.</p>

<p>TI-84: The TI-84 calculator has a built in F-distribution. Press [2<sup>=
nd</sup>] [DISTR] (this is F5: DISTR in the STAT app in the TI-89), then ar=
row down until you get to the Fcdf and press [Enter]. Depending on your cal=
culator, you may not get a prompt for the boundaries and df. If you just se=
e Fcdf( then you will need to enter each the lower boundary, upper boundary=
, <em>df</em><sub>1</sub>, and <em>df</em><sub>2</sub> with a comma between=
 each argument. The lower boundary is the 3.394 and the upper boundary is i=
nfinity (TI-83 and 84 use a really large number instead of =E2=88=9E), then=
 enter the two degrees of freedom. Press [Paste] and then [Enter], this wil=
l put the Fcdf(3.894,1E99,3,18) on your screen and then press [Enter] again=
 to calculate the value.</p>

